### Mail Autoconfig
* **Draft:** `draft-ietf-mailmaint-autoconfig`
* **Presenters:** Ben Bucksch
* **Slides:** [AutoConfig](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mailmaint-autoconfig-00) and [autoconfig outstanding issues](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mailmaint-autoconfig-outstanding-issues-00)
* **Overview & Deployment:** Ben Bucksch presented the status of the informational Autoconfig specification, highlighting its wide deployment (active on over 50,000 domains, representing roughly 8.5% of domains with MX records).
* **OAuth Metadata Duplication:** Aaron Parecki raised a design concern regarding duplicating the OAuth authorization and token endpoints within the autoconfig XML, suggesting clients could instead discover these via the issuer URL using OAuth server metadata. Ben Bucksch noted that relying on metadata discovery adds an extra query step and that not all OAuth implementations reliably support metadata endpoints. Aaron advised that if duplication remains, the document should explicitly justify this design choice to avoid future pushback.
* **Well-Known URIs vs. Legacy Paths:** The draft currently specifies a legacy path (`autoconfig.example.com`) established in 2008, which predates RFC 5785 (well-known URIs, 2010). 
    * Ricardo Signes noted security concerns with non-authoritative configuration sources. 
    * Arnt Gulbrandsen suggested documenting what existing deployments did up to yesterday without forcing a deprecation.
    * Daniel Kahn Gillmor (DKG) proposed keeping the document strictly informational to represent existing practice, which simplifies addressing concerns from the HTTP Directorate. Ben Bucksch agreed to add text acknowledging well-known URIs but clarifying that this document captures legacy, active deployments.
* **XML Elements & Validation:** 
    * Barry Leiba questioned the conflicting description of the `<emailProvider>` element (defined as having "no semantic purpose" but "significant content"). Ben Bucksch agreed to refine the wording.
    * Barry Leiba suggested moving the large XML example in Section 3.1 to an appendix. Ben Bucksch expressed a strong preference for keeping it in the main body to provide readers with an initial structural overview.
    * Pete Resnick and Barry Leiba questioned the use of RFC 2119 "should" and "must" keywords regarding display name character limits (e.g., 30/60 characters). Pete suggested removing "should" and instead describing the UI-rendering limitations on smaller devices.

