### Personal Data Portability Archive
* **Draft:** `draft-ietf-mailmaint-pdparchive`
* **Presenter:** Lisa Dusseault
* **Slides:** [PDP Archive](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-mailmaint-pdp-archive-00)
* **JSON Schema Integration:** Lisa Dusseault integrated JSON schemas into the draft to validate the JSON examples. 
    * DKG and Robert Stepanek supported keeping these schemas in the document (preferably in an appendix). Robert Stepanek (co-author of JS Calendar) agreed to coordinate with Lisa on schema placement.
* **Deleted Folders & Tombstones:** The draft discussed how to represent deleted folders in incremental backups.
    * Hans-Joerg Happel noted that some systems implement "soft deletes" (parking folders instead of purging them).
    * Ben Bucksch proposed keeping metadata about deleted folders in the parent folder's metadata. This prevents empty "deleted" directories from appearing when users extract the archive. Lisa agreed to explore this approach.
    * DKG highlighted the privacy tension of leaving metadata traces for deleted items. Bron Gondwana noted that keeping deletion records is mathematically necessary for functional incremental synchronization. Alexey Melnikov recommended addressing this trade-off in the Security Considerations section.
* **Synchronization vs. Migration:** Ricardo Signes questioned the need for complex incremental synchronization features instead of focusing strictly on one-shot migrations (like Google Takeout). Lisa explained that lightweight synchronization features (like UIDs) are essential to prevent severe duplicate data issues when importing archives multiple times.

